<section id="section-2">
<title> Application level (Angular momentum) </title>
<para id="element-64">
<exercise id="exercise-64">
<problem id="id1164491432571">
<para id="element-65">A particle of mass 100 gram is moving with a constant speed at √2 m/s along a straight line y = x + 2 in "xy" – plane. Then, the magnitude of the angular momentum (in 
<m:math>
<m:mfrac>
<m:mrow>
<m:mi> kg </m:mi>
<m:mo> - </m:mo>
<m:msup>
<m:mi> m </m:mi>
<m:mn> 2 </m:mn>
</m:msup>
</m:mrow>
<m:mrow>
<m:mi> s </m:mi>
</m:mrow>
</m:mfrac>
</m:math>
) about the origin of the coordinate system, if “x” and “y” are in meters, is :
</para>
<para id="element-66">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mi> (a) </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mn> 0.1 </m:mn>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> (b) </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mn> 0.2 </m:mn>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> (c) </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mn> 0.3 </m:mn>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> (d) </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mn> 0.4 </m:mn>
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
</problem>
<solution id="id1164491381332">

<para id="element-67">
The angular momentum of a particle about a point is defined as :
</para>
<para id="element-68">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mi mathvariant="bold"> ℓ </m:mi>
<m:mo> = </m:mo> 
<m:mi> m </m:mi>
<m:mo> ( </m:mo> 
<m:mi mathvariant="bold"> r </m:mi>
<m:mo mathvariant="bold"> x </m:mo> 
<m:mi mathvariant="bold"> v </m:mi>
<m:mo> ) </m:mo> 
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
<para id="element-69">
The magnitude of angular momentum can be evaluated using any of the three methods discussed in the module on the subject. In this case, evaluation of angular momentum involving moment arm is most appropriate. Thus,
</para>
<para id="element-70">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mi> ℓ </m:mi>
<m:mo> = </m:mo> 
<m:mi> m </m:mi>
<m:msub>
<m:mi> r </m:mi>
<m:mo> ⊥ </m:mo> 
</m:msub>
<m:mi> v </m:mi>
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
<para id="element-71">
